issue.title: Compiled binary is too big
issue.body:
- Robotgo version (or commit ref): fdaa440f26
- Go version: 1.15.3
- Gcc version: 9.2.0
- Operating system and bit: Windows 10 64 bit
- Resolution: 1920x1080
- Can you reproduce the bug at [Examples](https://github.com/go-vgo/robotgo/blob/master/examples/main.go):
  - [ ] Yes (provide example code)
  - [ ] No
  - [X ] Not relevant
- Provide example code:

```Go
package main

import "github.com/go-vgo/robotgo"

func main() {
	robotgo.TypeStr("Hello World!", 1.0)
}
```
- Log gist:

## Description

Compiling the above code with `go build -ldflags "-s -w"` produces a 4.1 MB binary. The corresponding code using [enigo](https://github.com/enigo-rs/enigo) in Rust produces a 244 kB binary. Since both are statically linked, I think that the comparison is fair. For reference, a calculator written in Go and Tk weighs 2.4 MB.

issue.title: Compiled binary is too big
issue.body:
- Robotgo version (or commit ref): fdaa440f26
- Go version: 1.15.3
- Gcc version: 9.2.0
- Operating system and bit: Windows 10 64 bit
- Resolution: 1920x1080
- Can you reproduce the bug at [Examples](https://github.com/go-vgo/robotgo/blob/master/examples/main.go):
  - [ ] Yes (provide example code)
  - [ ] No
  - [X ] Not relevant
- Provide example code:

```Go
package main

import "github.com/go-vgo/robotgo"

func main() {
	robotgo.TypeStr("Hello World!", 1.0)
}
```
- Log gist:

## Description

Compiling the above code with `go build -ldflags "-s -w"` produces a 4.1 MB binary. The corresponding code using [enigo](https://github.com/enigo-rs/enigo) in Rust produces a 244 kB binary. Since both are statically linked, I think that the comparison is fair. For reference, a calculator written in Go and Tk weighs 2.4 MB.
